Tort Reform <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Nice concept, difficult to implement.<br>
<br>
I have been part of several groups proposing tort reform in Florida.  My role has been as a trial lawyer (though a defense one) to provide input about what makes practical differences in day to day litigation.  I have spent hours telling consultants and lobbyists where we really need help, but the major fixes are not sexy enough for them.  They just HAVE to use the old standbys, like caps on damages, restrictions on punitive damages, and attacking the fees plaintiffs' lawyers get.<br>
<br>
Those are neat to talk about. But in the end, they are really not feasible to fix with sweeping legislation.  For example, Jeb is having a special session here in Tally just next week to talk about Medical Malpractice reform (specialized tort reform).  His big push?  To make pain and suffering damages cap out at $250,000.<br>
<br>
Now, there are two problems with that.  <br>
<br>
First, it does not take into account that some cases are worth more than that if the doctor really injured the person.  If an anesthesiologist is not paying attention during your surgery because he was out too late the night before, and you end up with brain damage, how can anyone say the non-economic damages are only $250,000?  Likewise, if your neurosurgeon messes up on your neck surgery and you become a quadraplegic, is $250,000 fair for the suffering associated with never moving anything below your chin again?<br>
<br>
Second, it makes no sense to give doctors a pass on med mal and hold everyone else liable for normal torts.  Why does a doctor who paralyzes you in surgery get a cap when he would not if he caused the same injury hitting you with his shiny new Jaguar?<br>
<br>
The REAL problem, as I see it, is that too many doctors who did NOT do anything wrong are afraid the juries will find them liable.  A plaintiff lawyer can get an expert to say anything.  We need to adopt stricter standards for experts, and the medical profession needs to cleain up its act in this regard.  Doctors should not complain about suits when it is their profession who puts out these &quot;doctors&quot; who will make up a liability theory for every occasion.  <br>
<br>
We also need to give judges more power to reduce verdicts.  That way, when you end up with a millions dollar verdict for a small injury, it can be reduced.  But, when the millions are awared for catastrophic cases, it can stand.<br>
<br>
But, like I said, these are boring fixes.<br>
<br>
Stumpey's prediction.  Jeb's reform will go through, and the Florida Supreme Court will declare it unconstitutional (along with the just-passed &quot;fixed&quot; workers-comp bill) in a matter of months. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=grimstafftheurgist>Grimstaff Theurgist</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/grimicon.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elder Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 8101<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/31/03 10:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2252.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/grim3.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Medical Malpractice Suits (@*&amp;^)</span><hr size=1> Tort Reform is absolutely critical, but its being looked at and worked on by... lawyers... so don't expect anything wonderful, just wordy.<br>
